1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 {Sometimes White also chooses to start with 3.g3
since that move would prevent the Queen's Indian from Black, however, it
allows extra options such as 3...Bb4+ or 3...c5, where White has already
committed the pawn on g3.} d5 4. g3 {This is the starting position of the
Catalan. In part one of the Catalan database, many important lines will be
analyzed, while this chapter will focus on the rare 4th moves from Black. The
main moves 4...Be7 followed by 5...0-0 and 4...Bb4+ will be analyzed in part 2
of the Catalan database.} g6 (4... Ne4 {This move is very rare although
sometimes it's played by strong players, more often in rapid or blitz games.
Black's idea is to push f5 and play a Stonewall set-up, but White is
well-prepared for this.} 5. Bg2 (5. Qc2 {Is also possible.}) 5... f5 (5... Bb4+
{The bishop isn't well-placed on b4 and it just helps White.} 6. Nbd2 f5 7. O-O
O-O 8. Ne5 $16 {White can play Ndf3 and Nd3 eventually.}) 6. O-O Be7 7. Be3 $5
$146 {White develops the bishop to e3 instead of f4 because g7-g5 may be an
idea for Black at some point with tempo. The idea of Be3 is to play Nbd2,
reroute the f3-knight to d3 via the e1-square, and then the knight from d2
goes to f3.} (7. Nc3 c6 8. Qc2 Nd7 9. Rb1 (9. Ne1 $5 {This is an interesting
move which is more useful than the moves that were played in the game. The
idea is to reroute the knight to d3 next.}) 9... a5 10. a3 O-O 11. Bf4 g5 12.
Bd2 Bf6 $132 {1/2-1/2 (52) Caruana,F (2792)-Rapport,R (2763) Baku 2021}) (7.
Qc2 {Is also possible.}) 7... c6 (7... O-O 8. Nbd2 Nc6 9. Qc2 a5 10. Rad1 $14 {
White can continue with the aforementioned plan of Ne1-Nd3 and then Ndf3.}) 8.
Nbd2 Nd7 9. Qc2 {White can bring the rook from a1 to d1 later on.} (9. Rc1 {
Is also an option.}) 9... O-O 10. Ne1 {[%cal Ge1d3,Gd2f3]} Ndf6 (10... Bf6 11.
Ndf3 {The knight comes to d3 and White has great control over the e5-square
and a typical slightly better position.}) 11. Ndf3 $14 {[%cal Ge1d3]} Ng4 $6
12. Bf4 {Provoking f5.} g5 13. Bc1 Bd6 14. Nd3 Qf6 {Black is trying to attack
although Black's pieces are slightly exposed, and White didn't do anything
wrong.} 15. b3 (15. Bh3 $5 {This is the computer's suggestion, although it's a
bit more complicated so I prefer 15.b3.}) 15... f4 16. h3 Nh6 17. g4 $16 {
[%cal Gf3e5] The pawn structure on the kingside is in White's favor, and White
can continue with Nfe5 and Bb2, while pushing e3 in order to open up the
position is also an idea.}) (4... b6 {Black wants to fianchetto the
light-squared bishop on b7 and it will transpose to some kind of a Queen's
Indian set-up, although a better version for White.} 5. cxd5 (5. Bg2 {Is
similar.}) 5... exd5 6. Bg2 Bb7 7. O-O Be7 8. Nc3 O-O {Transposes to a Queen's
Indian Defense where Black has committed with d5 a bit early, so this position
is considered slightly better for White.} 9. Bf4 {White also has other moves
to choose from, but 9.Bf4 is very good. White's usual plan is to play Rc1 and
Ne5, but I also like the additional plan of playing h4 and e3, strengthening
the position of the bishop on f4. Eventually White will put pressure on the d5
and c5-pawns (Black should play c7-c5 at some point since there will be
pressure on the pawn on c7.)} Na6 (9... Nbd7 10. Rc1 c6 {This may be slightly
better than 10...c5, although it's quite passive.} (10... c5 11. dxc5 Nxc5 (
11... bxc5 $6 12. Nh4 $1 {Putting more pressure on the d5-pawn.} Nb6 13. Nf5
$16 {White will capture the bishop on e7 and will enjoy a pleasant bishop pair
advantage in an open position.}) 12. Nb5 (12. Nd4 $14 {Is also possible.})
12... Ne6 (12... a6 13. Nbd4 $16) 13. Be5 $14 {White has an advantage and will
eventually place a knight on d4.}) (10... a6 11. Ne5 (11. Nh4 $5 {[%cal Gh4f5]
With the idea of playing Nf5 is also interesting in this particular position.})
11... Rc8 12. e3 $14 {This is a much better version for White since Black
can't play c5 due to the pressure on the d5-pawn, while 12...c5 13.dxc5 Nxc5
will make the d5-pawn isolated and weak, with a very pleasant position for
White.}) 11. e3 (11. Re1 {[%cal Ge2e4] This is also an option, with the idea
to play e2-e4.} Re8 12. e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Rxe4 Nf6 15. Re2 Nd5 $14 {
White has a slight advantage although Black is very solid, so that's why I
prefer to go 11.e3 instead of 11.Re1.}) 11... Re8 12. h4 $14 {[%csl Gf4]
Protecting the bishop's position on f4 just in case. White has ideas of
playing Bh3 and Ne5 at some point, while it's difficult for Black to push c5.
It's good to note that White isn't afraid of Nh5-Nxf4 since White can
recapture exf4 and continue with Ne5. Black's position is very passive,
especially with the light-squared bishop on b7.}) 10. Rc1 Re8 (10... c5 11.
dxc5 bxc5 (11... Nxc5 {Transposes to 9...Nbd7.}) 12. Qb3 {Putting some
pressure on Black's position and vacating the d1-square for the rook from f1.}
Qc8 (12... Qb6 $6 13. Qxb6 axb6 14. Nd2 $16 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd2c4] White
plans to use the pin on the h1-a8 diagonal with Nc4 and then Rfd1 next,
putting pressure on the pawns on b6 and d5.}) 13. Bh3 Qc6 {13...Bxh3 is met by
14.Qxb7 where both the bishop on e7 and knight on a6 are attacked.} 14. Ne5 Qb6
15. Bg2 Qxb3 16. axb3 Nb4 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 18. Nd3 {Exchanging the strong knight
on b4.} Nxd3 19. Rxd3 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5][%cal Gc3a4] White's idea is to put
pressure on the hanging pawns on c5 and d5. White has a very pleasant endgame
and can consider continuing with Be5 or Na4 next.}) 11. e3 c5 12. h4 $14 {
[%cal Gd1a4,Gf3e5,Gf1d1]}) (4... c6 5. Bg2 {Transposes later.}) (4... a6 5. Bg2
{Black should capture on c4 and it will transpose to variations which will be
analyzed later.}) (4... Nc6 5. Bg2 {Once again, Black should capture on c4 and
it will transpose to variations which will be analyzed later.}) (4... Nbd7 5.
Bg2 {Transposes later.}) 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 (7. Bf4 $5 {This move is
also possible.}) 7... Nc6 (7... dxc4 {This is a bit premature.} 8. Qa4 ({
White can choose to retrieve the pawn immediately with:} 8. Ne5 Nd5 9. Nxc4 Nc6
10. e3 $14) 8... a6 9. Qxc4 b5 10. Qb3 Bb7 11. a4 $16 {The pawn on b5 is
likely to fall since playing c6 is a bit awkward for Black, blocking the
light-squared bishop on b7.}) (7... Ne4 8. Qc2 Nc6 9. Rd1 f5 10. Be3 $16 {
White can continue with Rc1 and Ne5 eventually.}) (7... Nbd7 8. Bf4 dxc4 9. e4
$16 {White isn't afraid of giving up the pawn on c4 since the center is strong
and Qe2 is about to attack Black's pawn on c4. On c6 with the idea b5, White
can start with a4 in order to prevent the move b5, and then continue with Qe2.}
) (7... c6 8. Qc2 dxc4 (8... Nbd7 9. Bf4 {With a pleasant position for White.})
9. Rd1 Nbd7 (9... b5 10. a4 b4 11. Ne4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 {This is a very good
Catalan position for White.} Bb7 13. Bg5 Qc8 14. Nd2 c3 15. bxc3 bxc3 16. Nb3
Na6 17. Na5 $16 {White wants to capture the bishop on b7 and to play Rac1-Rxc3.
}) 10. e4 b5 11. Bf4 Bb7 12. Bd6 Re8 13. e5 Nd5 14. a4 (14. Ne4 {This is also
good enough.}) 14... Nxc3 15. Qxc3 Nb6 16. a5 Nd5 17. Qc1 {White is
threatening a5-a6.} a6 18. Ng5 $16 {Black has a lot of weaknesses and White
will play Ne4 eventually, so White is clearly better.}) 8. Ne5 $5 (8. b3 {
This is a safe approach with Bb2 or Bf4 next, but White can choose to be more
ambitious.}) 8... Nxe5 (8... Ne7 {This is very passive for Black.} 9. Qb3 c6
10. Rd1 $14 {White can consider playing e4 or Bf4 eventually.}) 9. dxe5 Ng4 {
This is a bit more aggressive from Black in comparison to 9...Nd7.} (9... Nd7
10. f4 {The central structure is very good for White and e2-e4 is an idea at
some point.} dxc4 (10... c6 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Be3 f6 13. exf6 Nxf6 14. Bd4 $16
{White has the better light-squared bishop, and continuing with Rc1 and e2-e4
is an idea.}) 11. Be3 $16 {[%cal Gc3e4] White wants to continue with Ne4, Qc2
and/or Rac1, and in any case, White will win back the pawn on c4 without too
much trouble.}) 10. f4 {Keeping the bishop on g7 blocked.} (10. cxd5 exd5 11.
Qxd5 Nxe5 12. Rd1 Qe7 $14 {White is better but Black isn't doing so bad either.
That's why I prefer 10.f4.}) 10... c6 (10... d4 11. Ne4 $16) (10... dxc4 11. h3
Nh6 12. Ne4 $16 {Black's pieces are inactive.}) 11. Kh1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gh2h3]
} h5 {Black's idea is to retreat the knight on h6 after White plays h3.} (11...
Qb6 {Now the position becomes very concrete and the best move is:} 12. e3 $1
Nxe3 13. Bxe3 Qxe3 14. Na4 $1 {[%csl Re3] Suddenly, Black's queen is in danger
and Re1 is coming.} b5 (14... a6 {With the idea to retreat the queen to the
a7-square is met by:} 15. c5 $18) 15. Re1 Qf2 16. Re2 Qxe2 17. Qxe2 bxa4 18.
Qd1 {Black doesn't have enough compensation and White simply wants to win the
pawn on a4.} a3 19. b3 a5 20. Qc1 $16) 12. h3 Nh6 13. e4 d4 {Black needs to
close the position since 13...dxe4 14.Nxe4 is terrible for Black, and 13...
dxc4 is also bad because the knight on h6 doesn't have any future.} 14. Na4 {
Preventing c6-c5.} b6 15. b4 f6 16. exf6 Qxf6 17. Nb2 {[%cal Gb2d3] The knight
is heading to the d3-square. 17.e5 is also a good option but it's more
concrete and it frees the f5-square for Black's knight.} e5 18. Nd3 Nf7 19. Bd2
Qe7 20. Rc1 $16 {The knight on d3 is very strong and Black has a lot of
weaknesses, so White is clearly better.} *

