1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 c5 {This move isn't very popular but it
transposes to a Tarrasch quite often, so it's a reasonable option for Black.}
5. Bg2 (5. cxd5 cxd4 $1 {This is a bit unusual but it's quite strong, and is
also the reason why I don't prefer 5.cxd5.} (5... exd5 {White's idea to play 6.
Bg2 and the position transposes to a system from the Tarrasch defense which is
slightly better for White.}) 6. dxe6 Bxe6 7. Qxd4 (7. Nxd4 Bc5 {The problem
for White is that 8.Nxe6? runs into 8...Bxf2+ where White loses the queen.} 8.
e3 Bxd4 9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. exd4 Nc6 $11 {Black is at least fine because of the
development advantage which compensates for the pawn deficit.}) 7... Nc6 8.
Qxd8+ Rxd8 {Black has already developed many pieces in comparison to White who
has only the knight on f3. White's king is stuck in the center and Nb4 is a
threat, so White is in an unpleasant position.} 9. Bg2 (9. a3 Ne4 $44 {[%cal
Gf8c5]}) 9... Nb4 10. Na3 Bc5 11. O-O O-O 12. Bg5 Nxa2 $11 {White may have a
slightly more pleasant position, but it's very close to being completely equal.
}) 5... Nc6 (5... dxc4 {Transposes to lesson 9.}) (5... cxd4 $5 6. O-O $1 {
It's important to start with this move.} (6. Nxd4 e5 {This is a different
theory.}) 6... Bc5 {This seems to be the best move for Black, although Black
also has some other options.} (6... dxc4 {If Black captures on c4, now it's
already important to exchange the queens.} 7. Qxd4 $1 Qxd4 (7... Nc6 8. Qxd8+
Nxd8 {If 8...Kxd8, White can continue with 9.Nbd2, eventually regaining the
pawn on c4.} 9. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Ge5c4,Gg2a8] This is a typical
Catalan endgame where White's light-squared bishop is much stronger than the
opponent's.}) 8. Nxd4 a6 {Black prevents any Nb5 ideas, but White can simply
continue developing.} (8... Bc5 9. Nb5 Na6 10. N1c3 O-O (10... e5 {Preventing
Bf4.} 11. Na4 Be7 12. Rd1 O-O 13. Be3 $16 {White is about to capture the pawn
on a7 and together with the strong bishop on g2, White is clearly better. In
addition, the bishop on c8 and knight on a6 are immobile.}) 11. Bf4 $16) (8...
Nd5 9. Nd2 c3 (9... Bc5 10. Nb5 {With threats such as Bxd5 or Nxc4.}) 10. bxc3
Nxc3 11. Bb2 {Even though White is a pawn down, the position is close to
winning due to a large lead in development.} Nd5 12. Nb5 a6 13. Nc3 $16 {
The position is highly unpleasant for Black.}) 9. Nd2 Bc5 10. Nc2 {It's good
to keep the bishop from g2 open, so that's why the knight retreats to c2 and
not to f3.} c3 11. bxc3 Nc6 12. Nc4 {White is trying to organize some play on
the weak b6-square.} Nd5 13. Bd2 {Protecting the c3-pawn.} b5 {Trying to play
actively is probably the best approach for Black in this position.} (13... O-O
14. a4 $14 {White wants to continue with moves such as a4-a5 and Rfb1. It's an
unpleasant position for Black where it's easy to go wrong, and on top of that,
it's difficult for Black to develop the bishop from c8.}) 14. Be3 $1 {The best
move for White.} Bxe3 15. N4xe3 Nce7 16. a4 Rb8 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 exd5 19.
Nb4 $14 {[%csl Rd5] White will win a pawn and although the position may be
defendable for Black, the game is one-sided and White has good winning chances.
}) (6... Be7 {This is a passive move from Black.} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Nxd4 O-O 9.
Qb3 {With the idea to play moves such as Rd1, Nc3, or e4.} Nc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6
11. e4 {The pawn structure is terrible for Black.} Nb4 (11... Nf6 12. Rd1 Qb6
13. Be3 Qxb3 14. axb3 $14 {The endgame is far from equal where Black's
weakness on a7 and c6 will count, while White can easily defend the pawn on b3
