pawn structure has some weaknesses, so White is slightly better.}) (7... Be6 8.
Nc3 Be7 (8... h6 9. b3 Be7 10. Bb2 O-O 11. Rc1 Rc8 12. dxc5 (12. e3 $5 {
Is also possible.}) 12... Bxc5 13. Na4 Be7 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 Ne4 16. Rc1
Qa5 17. a3 $14 {The position is one-sided and White has ideas like Nd4, Qd3,
or b4.}) 9. dxc5 $1 {After Be7, the bishop has spent a tempo so now already
White wants to capture on c5.} Bxc5 (9... d4 $6 10. Na4 $16) 10. Bg5 O-O 11.
Rc1 Be7 (11... Bb6 12. b3 $1 {The point is that White wants to capture on f6
and then on d5, where the pawn on b2 won't be attacked now.} d4 (12... Re8 13.
e3 $16 {[%csl Rd5] This prevents any d5-d4 push and White also has an idea of
rerouting the knight from c3 with Ne2-Nf4.}) 13. Ne4 Re8 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nc5
$16 {Black has a lot of weaknesses and the king is also exposed.}) 12. Nd4 Nxd4
(12... h6 $6 13. Be3 Ng4 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. Bd2 $16 {White can continue with
e2-e4 next.}) (12... Qd7 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Bh3 h6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. e4 $36 {
Black's position is very unpleasant. If 16...d4 17.Na4, White would have ideas
to reroute the knight to d3 with Nc5-Nd3, and another idea would be f4-e5,
with a simple position to play for White.}) 13. Qxd4 Qa5 (13... h6 14. Be3 Qd7
15. Rfd1 $14) 14. a3 Rfd8 15. Rfd1 h6 16. Bd2 Qa6 17. Be3 Ne4 18. Qd3 $1 {
It's best for White to exchange the queens since capturing on e4 and winning a
pawn will allow Black to gain some counterplay, and the e2-pawn may be hanging.
} Qxd3 19. Rxd3 Bf6 20. Bd4 $14 {The position is one-sided in White's favor.
Black's problem is that Rac8 isn't possible since after 20...Bxd4 21.Rxd4 Rac8
22.Bxe4 dxe4 23.Rxd8+ Rxd8 24.Nxe4, White wins a pawn with no compensation for
Black.}) 8. dxc5 $1 {The modern way to play this variation for White.} (8. Nc3
O-O {Leads to a big theoretical variation.}) 8... Bxc5 9. a3 {White wants to
continue with b4 and Bb2 next.} Ne4 {The only way for Black to fight for full
equality.} (9... a5 $6 {Giving up the b5-square looks a bit suspicious for
Black.} 10. Bg5 O-O 11. Qc2 $1 (11. Nc3 {Isn't so clear after:} d4 12. Ne4 Be7
$11) 11... Bb6 (11... Be7 12. Rd1 Be6 13. Nc3 h6 14. Be3 $16) 12. Nc3 d4 13.
Ne4 Re8 14. Rad1 Qe7 15. Nh4 $36 {The pin on the f6-knight is very unpleasant
and Black has a lot of problems.}) (9... O-O 10. b4 Be7 (10... Bb6 11. Nc3 Re8
{After 11...d4, White wants to play 12.Na4 to attack the bishop on b6, and
later to play Bb2 and attack the pawn on d4.} 12. Bb2 a6 13. e3 $16 {
Preventing d4 and White can continue with Na4 or Ne2-Nf4/Nd4 next.}) 11. Nc3
Be6 12. Bb2 Rc8 (12... Ne4 $6 13. b5 $1 Na5 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Nd4 $16 {It's
likely that the pawn on e4 will be lost.}) 13. Qd3 $1 {Preventing Ne4.} Qd7 14.
Rfd1 Rfd8 (14... Bf5 15. Qd2 {Doesn't change much in the position.}) 15. e3 $14
{White is slightly better with a very comfortable position thanks to the
isolated pawn on d5.}) 10. Nfd2 $1 {A very important move, trying to exchange
the knights.} ({Black's idea can be seen after:} 10. b4 Be7 11. Bb2 Bf6 12. Qc1
(12. Qb3 {Can be met with:} Be6) 12... O-O 13. Nbd2 Bf5 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bxf6
Qxf6 $11 {The bishop on e4 is active and there are ideas such as a7-a5 or Rac8,
so Black has good chances to equalize.}) 10... O-O {This is a newer move and
the only way to fight for equality according to the engines. 10...Nxd2 would
get Black in a worse and passive position, and after 11.Nxd2, White is
threatening Nb3, attacking both the bishop on c5 and the pawn on d5.} (10... f5
{This is the most played move but it doesn't equalize for Black.} 11. Nc3 Be6
12. Nb3 Bb6 13. Na4 $14 {Attacking the bishop on b6. The position seems a bit
suspicious for Black.}) 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Bxe4 Bd4 {Activating
the bishop and preventing Nc3.} 14. Kg2 $5 $146 {This is an improvement that
can be very unpleasant practically. White is preventing the move Bh3.} (14. Nc3
Bg4 {This is Black's idea, putting pressure on the e2-pawn.}) (14. Re1 Re8 15.
Nd2 {1-0 (73) Esipenko,A (2680)-Bjerre,J (2608) Vrnjacka Banja 2023} (15. Bg2
Bg4 16. Nc3 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Bxe2 18. Be3 Bd3 $11 {The position seems to be very
close to completely equal as even though White has the bishop pair, White also
has weak pawns on a3 and c3, and Be4 is an idea for Black.}) 15... h6 $44 {
Black's pieces are very active and it's not easy for White to make progress.})
14... Re8 (14... Be6 15. Nc3 $16 {White continues with the development of the
pieces.}) 15. Bf3 {White is not making any committal decisions for now.} (15.
Nd2 Bg4 16. e3 Bf6 $44 {White's pieces are a bit stuck and the control of the
d3-square has been weakened.}) 15... Ne5 {A logical move, trying to capture
the bishop on f3.} (15... Be6 16. Nc3 Bc4 17. Re1 Rad8 18. Bf4 $14 {Black
maybe can capture on c3 and damage White's pawn structure, but White would
have the bishop pair and is a pawn up, so Black has a long battle ahead to try
to defend successfully.}) (15... Bf6 $5 {[%cal Gc6d4]} 16. Nc3 Nd4 17. Nd5 Be5
18. Bf4 Nxf3 19. exf3 Be6 20. Nb6 {This is a good in-between move.} axb6 21.
Bxe5 $14 {This is probably a draw but White can try to press in this endgame
as White is a pawn up and g4 with Kg3 is an idea.}) 16. Bd5 {White wants to
continue with Nd2 next.} (16. Rd1 {Doesn't seem to be enough for White.} Nxf3
17. exf3 Be5 18. Nc3 Be6 19. Be3 a6 $14 {Black has a good pawn structure in
this case and the bishop pair, so it's very close to being completely fine for
Black.}) 16... Rd8 17. Be4 {An unusual bishop dance with the idea to provoke
f5.} (17. Bb3 {White removed the bishop from the h1-a8 diagonal so the
position seems to be okay for Black.} b6 18. Nc3 Ba6 19. Re1 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Rac8
$44) 17... f5 (17... Bg4 18. Re1 Nc4 19. Nc3 $14) 18. Bc2 Be6 19. Nc3 Rac8 (
19... Nc4 20. Nb5 Bb6 21. Bg5 Rdc8 22. Bb3 h6 23. Bc1 Bd5+ 24. Kg1 Rd8 25. Nc3
Bf7 26. Rb1 $14) 20. Bg5 Rf8 21. Bf4 {White gives up the pawn but will have
the bishop pair and the pieces will become active.} a6 {Preventing Nb5.} (21...
Bxc3 22. bxc3 Rxc3 23. Rfc1 $1 Ng6 24. Bd2 (24. Bxf5 {Unfortunately, this
tactic isn't working for White.} Nxf4+ 25. gxf4 Bd5+ 26. e4 Rxc1 27. Rxc1 Rxf5
$11) 24... Rc6 25. Ba4 Rcc8 26. f3 $14 {White has the bishop pair and is the
one who is pressing in this position.}) (21... Nc4 22. Bb3 $14) 22. Rfd1 Bxc3
23. bxc3 Rxc3 24. Bb1 Ng6 25. Bg5 Re8 26. a4 $14 {This is a slightly better
version for Black in comparison to 21...Bxc3 since White's light-squared
bishop is more passive in this position. White is still pressing and Black has
to defend well in order to equalize because White has the bishop pair and
a4-a5 is an idea too.} *

