1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 h6 {This move is becoming popular nowadays.
Black's idea is to continue with Bd6 and 0-0 next.} (4... Bd6 {White has
different options and move orders but it's logical to continue in the same way.
} 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O {Black has different options to choose from in this
position, from which 6...h6 will transpose to the main line arising from 4...
h6.} Nc6 (6... b6 7. Nc3 Bb7 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Nb5 $5 {This is a more ambitious
option for White.} (9. Ne5 {This seems to be the easiest option for White.}
Nbd7 10. Bf4 Re8 11. Nd3 Bxf4 12. Nxf4 c6 13. e3 $14 {With ideas like Qc2, Rc1,
and b4.}) 9... Be7 10. Bf4 Na6 11. e3 c6 12. Nc3 Nc7 13. h4 {White's not
bothered by the possibility that Black can capture the bishop on f4 since
White has very good control over the dark squares, especially the e5 square.}
Ne6 14. Qc2 Nxf4 15. exf4 Re8 (15... c5 $6 16. Rad1 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Rd5][%cal
Gf3e5]}) 16. Ne5 $14 {[%cal Gf1e1,Ga1d1]}) (6... dxc4 7. Ne5 c5 8. Nxc4 {
White successfully regained the pawn and now Black is in an unpleasant
position.} Nc6 (8... cxd4 9. Qxd4 Be7 10. Qxd8 Rxd8 11. Bd2 $5 (11. Nc3 Nc6 12.
Bf4 Nd5 {This isn't so clear, so it's best to play 11.Bd2.}) 11... Nc6 12. Rd1
{The point is that Black needs to be careful of the move e4 if Nd5 is played.}
Bd7 13. Nc3 Be8 14. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Gc4d6] White wants to continue with Nd6
next.}) 9. dxc5 (9. Nxd6 {Capturing the bishop seems nice, but it allows Black
some counterplay so this line isn't very clear.} Qxd6 10. dxc5 Qxc5 11. Nc3 Rd8
12. Qa4 Nd4 13. Rd1 e5 14. e3 Bd7 15. exd4 Bxa4 16. dxc5 Bxd1 17. Bg5 {White
sacrificed an exchange but now White's pieces became very active.} Bh5 18. Bxb7
Rab8 19. c6 Bf3 {The only move for Black.} 20. Re1 h6 21. c7 Bxb7 22. Be3 a6
23. Bb6 Re8 24. cxb8=Q Rxb8 25. Bc7 Re8 26. Rxe5 Rxe5 27. Bxe5 Ne4 $11 {
The position seems very close to being equal due to the opposite-colored
bishops, and even though White will avoid the knight exchange, Black's
position seems defendable.}) 9... Bxc5 10. Nc3 $14 {White is slightly better
and can continue with moves such as Bf4 or Qa4.}) (6... Nbd7 7. c5 $5 Be7 {
Black must retreat with the bishop to e7 and this is the difference with the
line where Nc3 and c6 are included.} 8. Nc3 Ne4 9. Qc2 f5 10. Bf4 c6 (10... g5
$6 11. Be3 {With an advantage for White.}) 11. Nxe4 fxe4 12. Ne5 $14 {White
has a small but very pleasant advantage.}) (6... c6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 (7... dxc4 $6
8. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gd2c4] White is going to recapture the pawn on c4 since
Black can't play b5 due to the Nxb5 tactic.}) (7... b6 8. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4]
White wants to play e4.} Ba6 9. b3 e5 (9... Nbd7 10. Bb2 {[%cal Ge2e4] White
develops with Bb2 and is about to strike in the center with e4.}) 10. dxe5 Bxe5
11. Bb2 Nbd7 12. Nf3 $1 dxc4 13. Nd4 $1 {Black must capture on d4 as there's
too much pressure on the c6-pawn.} Bxd4 14. Qxd4 Qc7 15. Ne4 $5 (15. bxc4 {
This is also possible, although White can choose to play with the initiative
instead.} Nc5 16. Qh4 $14) 15... cxb3 16. axb3 Bxe2 17. Rfc1 $36 {White's very
active pieces offer excellent compensation for the two pawns deficit.}) 8. Nd2
$5 {[%cal Ge2e4] When Black's bishop is on d6, White has this strong plan -
Nd2 and e4!} Re8 (8... Be7 9. a4 $5 $146 {This is an improvement, provoking a5.
} ({Black's idea is to meet} 9. e4 {with:} dxe4 10. Ndxe4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 e5 12.
d5 f5 13. Nc3 e4 $13) 9... a5 (9... b6 $6 {Now the h1-a8 diagonal is more open,
so White can play e4.} 10. e4 dxc4 11. Nxc4 Ba6 12. b3 Bxc4 13. bxc4 e5 14. Ne2
$16 {Keeping the tension in the center and intending to recapture on d4 with
the knight. White can also consider continuing with f2-f4 later on.}) (9... e5
10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 (11... cxd5 12. Nb3 $14) 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Nb3 $14
{The knight will eventually land on the d4-square.}) 10. b3 e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5
12. cxd5 cxd5 13. Bb2 $14 {Besides the isolated pawn on d5 and the d4-square,
White also has the b5-square available as an outpost.}) 9. e4 e5 (9... dxe4 $6
{This is a mistake from Black which occurred in hundreds of games.} 10. Ndxe4
Nxe4 (10... Bc7 11. b3 $16) 11. Nxe4 Bf8 12. Bf4 $16 {This is a very bad
position for Black since White has a big space advantage and Black can't play
either...e5 or ...c5.}) 10. dxe5 (10. exd5 {Leads to an unclear position.} exd4
11. Nce4 Bb4 12. dxc6 bxc6 13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 14. Bxc6 Bd7 $13) 10... Nxe5 11. cxd5
cxd5 12. exd5 Bg4 13. Qb3 $14 {Black has some compensation for the pawn, but
White is the one playing for a win and can continue with ideas such as Nc4 or
Ne4.}) 7. b3 {This is a typical move in these types of positions, simply
protecting the c4-pawn first and then continuing the development with Nc3.} (7.
Nc3 dxc4 $1 8. Qa4 e5 $11) 7... dxc4 (7... b6 8. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gb1c3] This
is very unpleasant for Black as now the f6-knight is pinned, Nc3 is coming,
and there is a lot of pressure on the d5-pawn and h1-a8 diagonal.}) (7... h6 8.
Bb2 b6 9. Nbd2 Bb7 10. a3 a5 11. Qc2 $16) (7... a5 8. Nc3 {Doesn't change much.
}) 8. bxc4 e5 {White's knight is on b1, so White can continue with:} 9. c5 $1
Be7 10. dxe5 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Ne4 12. Ba3 {It's good for White to be ready to
exchange the dark-squared bishops.} Bxc5 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. Nc3 Be6 15. Rdc1
Rad8 16. Nb5 Na6 {Black's pieces are passive and this endgame is good for
White.} 17. Ng5 Bd5 18. f4 $14 {White simply protects the e5-pawn and
continuing with Ne4 is an idea. Black has a tough battle ahead in trying to
defend this position.}) 5. Bg2 Bd6 6. O-O O-O 7. b3 $5 {The most flexible and
probably the best move for White.} (7. Nc3 Nc6 8. b3 dxc4 9. bxc4 e5 {This is
Black's idea which is also a theoretical variation where Black is more or less
fine. That's why I suggest the move 7.b3.}) 7... b6 (7... c5 8. cxd5 exd5 (8...
Nxd5 $6 9. Bb2 Nc6 10. e4 Nb6 11. e5 Be7 12. dxc5 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Bxc5 14. Nc3
$16 {[%cal Gc3e4] Ne4 is coming, the pawn on e5 is very good, and Black's
light-squared bishop is extremely passive, so White has an advantage.}) 9. Bb2
Nc6 10. Nc3 Re8 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. e3 $14 {White can continue with Rc1 and then
either Ne2 or Nb5.}) (7... Nc6 {Transposes to 4...Bd6.}) 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. Bb2 {
This is the main position where Black has played the move h6 which is a bit
strange, and so is the bishop's placement on the d6-square. In any case, White
is slightly better and Black is the one that should be careful.} Nbd7 (9... a6
$6 10. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4] This is one of the main plans for White, preparing
e2-e4.} c5 11. dxc5 $1 (11. cxd5 cxd4 12. Nce4 Bxd5 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Ne4 Bxe4
15. Bxe4 Ra7 16. Qxd4 Nd7 17. Qxf6 Nxf6 18. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Gb2,Gd3] White has
a small advantage in this endgame due to the bishop pair, but White can aim
for more with 11.dxc5.}) 11... Bxc5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. e3 Re8 14. Rc1 Nbd7 15.
Nf3 $16 {White has a comfortable position playing against the isolated pawn on
d5.}) (9... Ne4 10. Qc2 {Black doesn't really want to create more weaknesses
with f5, and after:} Nd7 11. Nb5 $14 {White wants to capture Black's
dark-squared bishop and retreating with Be7 isn't possible due to cxd5 where
the c7-pawn will be lost.}) (9... Re8 10. Qc2 a6 11. Rad1 Nbd7 12. Nd2 $14 {
[%cal Ge2e4]}) 10. Nd2 $5 {[%cal Ge2e4] Both options 10.Rc1 and 10.Nd2 give
White a slight advantage and both lead to an unpleasant position for Black.} (
10. Rc1 Re8 11. Qc2 ({Going after the c7 doesn't work after:} 11. cxd5 Nxd5 12.
Nb5 Bf8 13. e4 a6 $1 {Black has this strong resource that prevents White from
winning the c7-pawn.}) 11... a6 12. Rfd1 Rc8 13. Ne1 $5 {[%cal Gg2b7] This is
the best try for White, trying to use the pin on the d5 pawn on the h1-a8
diagonal.} Ba8 14. Na4 Bf8 ({The idea of Na4 can be seen after:} 14... c5 15.
dxc5 bxc5 16. e3 Bf8 17. Qe2 $14 {Black's position is unpleasant since the
pawn on a6 may be hanging in some lines and White can continue with the move
Nd3.}) 15. Nd3 ({After:} 15. c5 Bc6 {The position isn't so clear.}) 15... dxc4
16. bxc4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 {Black should play accurately now.} Qe7 {This is the
best move.} (17... c5 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. Bc3 Qc7 20. f3 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gc1b1]
This is more pleasant for White since Black has some weaknesses and White can
continue with Rb1 and e4.}) 18. Kg1 {Trying to avoid any unpleasant checks on
the h1-a8 diagonal in the future.} Red8 19. c5 Qe8 20. e3 $14) 10... Be7 {
This is Black's best move, losing a tempo but anticipating the move e4.} (10...
Bb4 {Giving up the dark-squared bishop isn't a good idea for Black.} 11. a3
Bxc3 12. Bxc3 c5 13. Rc1 $14 {Having the bishop pair, the position is clearly
in White's favor.}) (10... c5 11. cxd5 Nxd5 (11... exd5 12. Nc4 Be7 13. Ne3
cxd4 14. Qxd4 Bc5 15. Qf4 $16 {There's a lot of pressure on the d5-pawn and
it's likely that Black will also need to give up the dark-squared bishop for
the knight on e3.}) 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. e4 {This is a forced line.} Bb7 14. Nc4
Be7 15. d5 exd5 16. exd5 Bf6 17. Qd2 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 Nf6 19. Rfd1 $14 {The pawn
on d5 and knight on c4 give White an advantage, while Black's bishop on b7 is
blocked. The position is playable for Black but it's very unpleasant.}) 11. e4
dxe4 12. Ndxe4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Rb8 {Defending the bishop on b7 and trying to
play Nf6 next.} 14. Qc2 Nf6 15. Rad1 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Bxe4 17. Qxe4 $14 {The
position is slightly better for White and Black will need to defend for a
while. After 17...Bf6, White can consider improving the position with Bc1 and
then Be3 or Bf4, and the move h4 is also a possibility.} *

