1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 {This is one of the most-principled
and most aggressive options for Black.} 5. Bg2 {Black has a lot of options in
this position, and in this lesson, the move 5...b5 will be analyzed.} b5 $6 {
Playing b5 immediately is not a good option for Black. If Black wants to play
b5, it's better to prepare it with the moves a6 or c6 first.} 6. a4 {The main
move, immediately attacking the b5-pawn.} (6. Ne5 $5 Nd5 7. O-O {This is also
good for White, and the lines may transpose into each other.}) 6... c6 {
This is the main move which is objectively worse than 6...Bb7.} (6... b4 $6 7.
Ne5 Nd5 8. O-O $16 {White will regain the pawn eventually and will have a very
good position as the bishop is very strong from g2 and e4 is an idea.}) (6...
Bb7 {If Black doesn't want to play 6...c6, this is an option that Black can
choose.} 7. axb5 a6 8. bxa6 Nxa6 {This is the critical position where White
has many different options.} 9. Nbd2 {This is the easiest option for White,
trying to regain the pawn immediately.} (9. Qa4+ Nd7 10. Qb5 $1 {The best move
for White, attacking the bishop on b7.} Nb4 {The only move for Black.} (10...
Rb8 11. Qxc4 Bd5 12. Qc2 Nb4 13. Qd1 {White safely retreated the queen and now
is a clear pawn up. Nc3 can be played next.} c5 14. Bf4 Rc8 15. dxc5 Bxc5 16.
Nc3 $16) 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 12. Ne5 {This was the idea with the move 10.Qb5, now
both the bishop on b7 and knight on d7 are attacked.} c6 13. Qxc4 Ba6 (13...
Nxe5 14. dxe5 Be7 (14... Ba6 15. Qe4 $16 {White will castle next.}) 15. Qg4 $5
{White can also castle but this move is better.} Nc2+ 16. Kf1 Qa1 17. Be4 {
This is White's idea. The line is a little bit complicated, but it works well
for White.} Qxb1 18. Kg2 {White is a piece down temporarily but the knight on
c2 is pinned and the queen can't move, while castling isn't an option for
Black due to Bh6.} g6 19. Kh3 $1 {The best move. The king is safe on h3.} h5 (
19... O-O $2 20. Bg5 $18) 20. Qf3 Nd4 21. Qe3 Qa2 22. Qxd4 c5 23. Qd3 Bxe4 24.
Qxe4 O-O 25. Rd1 $16 {White is a clear pawn up with good winning chances.}) 14.
Bxc6 (14. Qc3 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd5 16. Qc2 Bb4+ 17. Bd2 O-O $14 {This line
arising from 14.Qc3 isn't very clear since it's difficult for White to castle
due to the pressure on the e2-pawn, so Black has some compensation.}) 14...
Nxc6 15. Qxc6 Qxc6 16. Nxc6 Bb7 17. d5 Nf6 18. Na5 Bxd5 19. O-O Ne4 (19... Bb4
{Is met by:} 20. Bd2 {Defending the knight on a5.}) 20. Nc3 Nxc3 21. bxc3 Be7
22. c4 Ba8 23. Be3 $16 {The position may be holdable for Black, although White
is a pawn up and Black has a long way to go in order to defend successfully.})
(9. Bg5 $5 {Not trying to regain the pawn immediately is also an interesting
option for White.} Nb4 10. Rxa8 Qxa8 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. O-O {White damaged
Black's pawn structure on the kingside and will try to regain the pawn next
with Nbd2.}) (9. O-O $5 {Also makes sense.}) 9... Nb4 10. Rxa8 Qxa8 11. Nxc4
Bd5 12. Ne3 Be4 13. O-O $16 {Black has some compensation for the pawn, but
White is a pawn up after all and Black will need to demonstrate good defensive
skills.}) 7. Ne5 {The best move for White.} (7. axb5 $5 {Capturing on b5 is
also an option.} cxb5 8. Ne5 Nd5 9. Nc3 {The position will probably transpose
to the main line after 9...Be7 or 9...Bb4.}) 7... Nd5 (7... Bb4+ 8. Nc3 Nd5 9.
axb5 {The position is already very suspicious for Black.} cxb5 (9... Nxc3 10.
bxc3 Bxc3+ 11. Bd2 Qxd4 (11... Bxa1 $2 12. Qxa1 $18 {White has tremendous
compensation for the exchange.}) 12. Nf3 $1 {The best move for White.} Bxd2+
13. Nxd2 O-O 14. bxc6 c3 15. Nb3 Qb4 16. Na5 {The point can be seen after
Black plays c2, White can block with Qd2 and the knight on b3 won't be under
attack.} Na6 17. c7 Nxc7 18. Bxa8 Nxa8 19. Qa4 $16 {Trying to exchange the
queens. White will win one of the a or c-pawns sooner or later, and the
endgame is very close to be winning for White.}) 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 (11. e4
$5 {This is also an option with the idea to capture the knight on d5 and then
bring the queen out to h5 or f3.}) 11... O-O (11... Nxc3 12. Qc2 Nd5 13. Ba3
