{[%evp 0,49,19,31,25,-11,-9,-1,0,-19,-6,-37,16,34,59,62,62,21,47,45,40,56,50,
-6,23,23,38,28,3,-21,36,36,42,9,0,-29,0,0,0,0,106,103,99,99,82,0,0,0,0,0,0,0]} 
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 c6 {With this move Black
somewhat blunts the Catalan bishop and prepares to hold on to the c4-pawn with
b7-b5.} 6. Ne5 {Trying to recover the pawn immediately. White has two
important alternatives, both highly theoretical and leading to interesting
play:} (6. O-O b5) (6. a4 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 a5) 6... Bb4+ {The main move.} (6... c5 {
At the cost of a tempo, Black immediately strikes against White's centre,
which has been neglected by his last move. Again, White has several options:}
7. Qa4+ {The other logical continuation, making use of the fact that Black is
not only behind in development but has also weakened himself on the a4-e8
diagonal.} (7. O-O {is only good enough for equality:} cxd4 8. Nd2 Be7 9. Ndxc4
O-O 10. b3 Nfd7 11. Qxd4 Nxe5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Nxe5 f6 14. Nc4 Nc6 15. Bxc6
bxc6 16. Be3 c5 $11) (7. Be3 $5 {Quickly developing while keeping the centre
under control.} Nd5 {The only consistent move, forcing some concessions  
(structure, bishop pair) but also falling further behind in development.} 8.
